[[File:Kazaskers of Rumeli and Anatolia.png|thumb|right|The two kazaskers in a 17th-century illustration]] A '''kazasker''' or '''kadıasker''' ({{lang-ota|قاضی عسكر}}, ''ḳāḍī'asker'', "military judge") was a chief judge in the [[Ottoman Empire]], so named originally because his jurisdiction extended to the cases of soldiers, who were later tried only by their own officers.<ref>Webster (1913), ''sub voce''</ref>{{better source|date=September 2016}} Two kazaskers were appointed, called ''[[Rumelia|Rumeli]] Kazaskeri'' and ''[[Anatolia|Anadolu]] Kazaskeri'', having their jurisdiction respectively over the European and the Asiatic part of the Empire. They were subordinated to the [[Grand Vizier]], later [[Sheikh ul-Islam|Şeyhülislam]], and had no jurisdiction over the city of [[Istanbul|Constantinople]]. Moreover, they attended the meetings at the [[Imperial Council (Ottoman Empire)|Imperial Council]].<ref>Mantran (1995), pp. 115-16 </ref>
A Kazasker handled appeals to the decisions of [[kadı]]'s, had the power to overrule these, and suggested kadı candidates to the Grand Vizier.
