{{History of Sudan}}
The '''Revolutionary Command Council for National Salvation''' ('''RCCNS-Sudan''') was the governing body of [[Sudan]] following the [[1989 Sudanese coup d'état|June 1989 coup]].<ref name="Cowell">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/07/01/world/military-coup-in-sudan-ousts-civilian-regime.html|title=Military Coup In Sudan Ousts Civilian Regime|last=Cowell|first=Alan|date=July 1, 1989|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=February 19, 2017|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|work=|via=}}</ref> It grew out of the collaboration between the Sudanese military and the [[National Islamic Front]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YyYuzczwY94C&pg=PA269&dq=Revolutionary+Command+Council+for+National+Salvation&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwic6_nJspzSAhUn_IMKHdY_Cu0Q6AEIQjAH#v=onepage&q=Revolutionary%20Command%20Council%20for%20National%20Salvation&f=false|title=In Whose Image? Political Islam and Urban Practices in Sudan|last=T. Abdou Maliqalim Simone|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=1994|isbn=0226758702|location=|pages=64|quote=|via=}}</ref> It was the authority by which the military government of [[Sudan]] under Lt. Gen. [[Omar Al-Bashir|Omar al-Bashir]] exercised power.

Al-Bashir was the Chair of the Council, as well as Prime Minister, Defense Minister and Commander-in-Chief of the [[Sudanese Armed Forces]].<ref name="Cowell"/> The rest of the council consisted of fourteen military officers, all of whom were involved in and associated with the coup.<ref name ="Burr and Collins"/>{{rp|p. 2}} Therefore, no regulations about the selection and tenure of its members were declared to the public.

The RCCNS exercised legislative as well as some executive authority.  It appointed committees to draft various legal decrees. The RCCNS did not publish any rules of procedures over its deliberations.

It banned political activity, arrested opposition members and closed down newspapers.

The RCCNS dissolved itself in October 1993, and its powers devolved to the [[List of heads of state of Sudan|President]] and the [[National Legislature (Sudan)|National Legislature of Sudan]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Government and Politics of the Middle East and North Africa|publisher=Westview Press|year=1995|isbn=0813321263|editor-last=Long|editor-first=David|location=|pages=344|quote=|editor-last2=Reich|editor-first2=Bernard|via=}}</ref> This resulted in a majority of the power remaining with President al-Bashir.<ref name ="Burr and Collins">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ySUK3qoP-bsC&pg=PA2&lpg=PA2&dq=members+of+the+Revolutionary+National+Command+Council+for+National+Salvation&source=bl&ots=BBG9dZcGUw&sig=-ypU5jCn717ByuHhY9WxnJ9Akms&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi9g5vou5zSAhVF6IMKHfvSAko4ChDoAQgtMAc#v=onepage&q=Revolutionary%20Command%20Council&f=false|title=Revolutionary Sudan: Hasan Al-Turabi and the Islamist State, 1989-2000|last=Burr|first=J. Miller|last2=Collins|first2=Robert|publisher=Brill|year=2003|isbn=9004131965|quote=|via=}}</ref>{{rp|p. 131}}

